      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the world of real estate, where even the most mundane tasks are often guarded by the watchful eyes of a gnome or two. In this case, the gnome is the escrow account, a magical vault where all the gold and treasures (or in your case, money and documents) are kept safe until the grand finale of the house-hunting quest.\n\nEscrow is like a trusty goblin who holds onto your hard-earned coins until the deed is done. It ensures that neither the buyer nor the seller can just waltz away with the treasure before the final handshake. This goblin-like escrow account makes sure that the seller hands over the keys to the castle (the house) and the buyer hands over the gold (the money) only when both parties have fulfilled their promises. It's a way to keep the peace and ensure that the house-hunting adventure ends on a happy note, with no goblins lurking in the shadows to steal your gold.",
