      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait, gnomes and goblins? lol i meant the actual legal process. i'm trying to understand the logistics for my lawyer. is it just a bank account or a specific type of legal setup? and who exactly is in charge of it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, my apologies for the whimsical detour! Let's get back to the serious business of real estate and the trusty escrow account, shall we? No gnomes or goblins here, just the hard facts.\n\nAn escrow account is indeed a special type of bank account, but it's not just any bank account. It's a secure place where funds and important documents are held by a neutral third party, known as the escrow agent, until all the conditions of the real estate transaction are met. This ensures that both the buyer and the seller fulfill their obligations before the deal is finalized.\n\nThe escrow agent is typically a title company, an attorney, or a bank, depending on the jurisdiction and the preferences of the parties involved. They act as the guardian of the transaction, making sure that the seller provides a clear title to the property and that the buyer pays the agreed-upon purchase price. Once all the conditions are met, the escrow agent releases the funds to the seller and the property documents to the buyer, completing the transaction.\n\nI hope this clears up the confusion and helps you understand the role of the escrow account in the closing process. If you have any more questions, feel free to ask!",
      "source": "target",
